---
description: >-
  Apply DDD Hexagonal architecture for Hono backend services. Use when creating
  or modifying files in any backend app (auth-api, app-registry, entitlements,
  feature-flags).
globs: >-
  apps/auth-api/**/*.ts,apps/app-registry/**/*.ts,apps/entitlements/**/*.ts,apps/feature-flags/**/*.ts
alwaysApply: false
tags:
  - architecture
  - backend
  - typescript
---

Hexagonal Architecture (Ports/Adapters):

- `domain/` = pure business logic, ZERO external dependencies
- `application/` = use cases, DTOs, orchestration
- `infrastructure/` = adapters, HTTP routes, config

Domain Layer Rules:

- NO import from `hono`, `prisma`, `redis`, `ioredis`, `openai` in `domain/`
- NO import from `hono`, `prisma` in `application/`
- Entities and Value Objects are plain TypeScript classes
- Ports are interfaces defined in `domain/ports/` or `packages/hub-contracts`

Dependency Direction:

- `infrastructure/` → `application/` → `domain/` (inward only)
- `domain/` NEVER depends on outer layers
- Use manual DI in `index.ts` to provide adapters to use cases (ADR-028)

Hono Scope:

- Hono is ONLY in `infrastructure/` (routes, middleware, error handler)
- Each service has a single `index.ts` composition root
- Route files create sub-apps via `new Hono()` and are mounted with `app.route()`

Mandatory Patterns (ADR-012):

- Strategy: swap implementations (auth provider, event bus, storage)
- Adapter: normalize external interfaces to internal contracts
- Repository: abstract persistence behind domain interfaces
- Facade: simplify complex subsystem access
- Circuit Breaker: prevent cascade failures on inter-service calls
- Observer: decouple producers and consumers via events

Anti-Patterns:

- Avoid importing `PrismaClient` directly in use cases
- Avoid Hono or framework imports in domain or application layers
- Avoid anemic domain models (put behavior in entities)
- Avoid god modules (split by bounded context)
